{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.04,0.26,0.07,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111061"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10016"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93181"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"3845"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45133"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111061"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of vulval itch and soreness. She has tried over-the-counter antifungal creams without improvement. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is post-menopausal and has had three normal cervical screening tests, most recently two years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a well-demarcated, erythematous, slightly raised plaque on the right labium majus with scattered white areas. The lesion is not indurated and there is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate next step for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referral for biopsy","Oral fluconazole","Topical hydrocortisone","Intravaginal oestrogen pessary","Vulval swab for microscopy and culture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic vulval itch and a persistent, well-demarcated erythematous plaque with scattered white areas, unresponsive to antifungal therapy, are classic features of extramammary Paget disease of the vulva. The next step is to confirm the diagnosis and exclude underlying malignancy. \u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is essential, as it allows histopathological identification of Paget cells within the epidermis and assessment for invasive disease or associated adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat vulval candidiasis, which typically presents with acute symptoms and responds to antifungal therapy. The chronicity and lack of response to topical antifungals make candidiasis unlikely in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E may be used for inflammatory dermatoses such as contact dermatitis or lichen simplex, but these conditions would be expected to improve with appropriate topical therapy and removal of irritants. The persistent, well-demarcated lesion described here is not typical of these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravaginal oestrogen pessary\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for atrophic vaginitis, which presents with dryness, irritation, and sometimes soreness, but not with a persistent plaque as described. The examination findings are not consistent with atrophic changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVulval swab for microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if bacterial or fungal infection were suspected. However, the clinical presentation with a well-demarcated plaque and lack of response to antifungal therapy makes infectious causes unlikely, and this would not address the concerning morphology of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiopsy is therefore the most appropriate next diagnostic step to confirm the diagnosis and guide further management, including assessment for underlying adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Biopsy is essential to confirm the diagnosis of Paget disease of the vulva and to exclude malignancy.","Persistent vulval itch and a well-demarcated erythematous plaque unresponsive to standard treatments should prompt consideration of Paget disease.","Other common vulval conditions may mimic Paget disease but typically respond to first-line therapies or have distinguishing features."],"references":["Parashurama R, Nama V, Hutson R. Paget\u2019s Disease of the Vulva: A Review of 20 Years\u2019 Experience. International Journal of Gynecologic Cancer [Internet]. 2017 May 1 [cited 2024 Dec 12];27(4). Available from: https://ijgc.bmj.com/content/27/4/791"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93181"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T19:49:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-11T18:48:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10016"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111061"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes"